'''''Tetris''''', also known as '''classic ''Tetris''''', is a [[puzzle video game]] for the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]] (NES) released in 1989, based on ''[[Tetris]]'' (1985) by [[Alexey Pajitnov]]. It was published after a legal battle between Nintendo and Atari Games, who had [[Tetris (Atari Games)|already released a ''Tetris'' NES port]] under a license that was found to be invalid. [[Bullet-Proof Software]] had previously published [[List of Tetris variants|''Tetris'' for the Family Computer]] in December 1988,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bps.co.jp/04_products/index31.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20000823075808/http://www.bps.co.jp/04_products/index31.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=August 23, 2000|title=Products: Family Computer|publisher=Bullet-Proof Software}}</ref> while Nintendo had published [[Tetris (Game Boy video game)|''Tetris'' for the Game Boy]] earlier in 1989.

This ''Tetris'' port is unusual because the game is designed to end by becoming too fast to play, after a certain number of [[Tetris#Gameplay|lines are cleared]]. Score must be accumulated through efficient play, rather than pure endurance, before the game ends. These circumstances have lead to its use as an [[esports]] game. Although the highest game speed was intended to be unplayably difficult, it was shown to be manageable with novel controller grips developed in the 2020s.

==Gameplay==
{{see also|Tetris#Gameplay}}
This version of ''Tetris'' has two modes of play: A-Type and B-Type. In A-Type play, the goal is to achieve the highest score. As lines are cleared, the level advances and increases the speed of the falling blocks. In B-Type play, the board starts with randomized obstacle blocks at the bottom of the field, and the goal is to clear 25 lines. The level remains constant, and players choose the height of the obstacle beforehand.<ref name="manual">{{cite book |title=Tetris Instruction Booklet |publisher=[[Nintendo of America]] |location=USA |year=1989 |url=https://www.gamesdatabase.org/media/system/nintendo_nes/manual/formated/tetris_-_1988_-_tengen_ltd..pdf |access-date=October 3, 2021 }}</ref>

[[File:Tetris NES play.png|thumb|left|A-Type game]]
During play, the [[Tetris#Game pieces|tetrominoes]] are chosen randomly. This leaves the possibility of extended periods with no long bar pieces, which are essential because [[Tetris#Scoring|Tetrises]] are worth more than clearing the equivalent amount of lines in singles, doubles, or triples. The next piece to fall is shown in a preview window next to the playfield. In a side panel, the game tracks how many of each tetromino has appeared in the game so far.<ref name="manual"/>

In A-Type, the level advances for every 10 lines cleared. Each successive level increases the points scored by line clears and changes the colors of the game pieces.<ref name="manual"/> All levels from 1 to 10 increase the game speed. After level 10, the game speed only increases on levels 13, 16, 19, and 29,{{efn|name=PAL killscreen|This is only the case on the [[NTSC]] version of the game. On [[PAL]] the last speed change happens at level 19, which is that version's "kill screen".}} at which point the speed no longer increases. On level 29, pieces fall at 1 grid cell every frame, which is too fast for almost all players, and it is thus called the "[[kill screen]]".<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |last=Trew |first=James |date=May 6, 2022 |title=How Gen Z is pushing NES Tetris to its limits |url=https://www.engadget.com/teens-tetris-and-rolling-130002013.html |access-date=2023-04-19 |website=[[Engadget]] |language=en-US}}</ref> The developers of the game never intended anyone to play past the kill screen, as the game does not properly display the level numbers past 29,<ref name="good">{{Cite web |last=Good |first=Owen S. |date=2019-04-13 |title=Elite Tetris player takes the NES version where no one has gone before |url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/4/13/18309474/tetris-kill-screen-level-33-record-joseph-saelee |access-date=2023-04-19 |website=Polygon |language=en-US}}</ref> but with modern [[#Speed techniques|speed techniques]], skilled players can play past level 29.<ref name="sweet">{{cite magazine |url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/cultural-comment/the-revolution-in-classic-tetris |title=The Revolution in Classic Tetris |last=Sweet |first=Jacob |date=March 26, 2021 |magazine=[[The New Yorker]] |access-date=October 3, 2021}}</ref><ref name=":0" />

When starting a game, players can select a starting level from 0 to 9, but if the A button is held on the controller when selecting a level, 10 additional levels are added, raising the starting options to 0 to 19.<ref name="manual" /> When starting on a later level, the level is not supposed to advance until as many lines have been cleared as it would have taken to advance from level 0 to the starting level.<ref name="manual" /> Due to a bug, the levels will begin advancing earlier than intended when starting on level 10 or higher.<ref name="meatfighter" />

[[File:Moscow StBasilCathedral d28.jpg|right|thumb|[[Saint Basil's Cathedral]] appears in the title screen and ending, alluding to the [[Tetris#History|Soviet origin of ''Tetris'']].<ref name="sheff">{{cite book |last=Sheff |first=David |author-link=David Sheff |date=1994 |title=[[Game Over (Sheff book)|Game Over]]: How Nintendo Conquered The World |location=United Kingdom |publisher=Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group |page= |isbn=978-0307800749}}</ref>]]
At the end of an A-Type game, a substantial score yields an animated ending of a rocket launch in front of [[Saint Basil's Cathedral]]. The size of the rocket depends on the score, ranging from a [[bottle rocket]] to the [[Buran (spacecraft)|''Buran'' spaceplane]]. In the best ending, a [[Unidentified flying object|UFO]] appears on the launch pad and the cathedral lifts off.<ref name="meatfighter">{{cite web |url=https://meatfighter.com/nintendotetrisai |title=Applying Artificial Intelligence to Nintendo Tetris |last=Birken |first=Mike |date=January 28, 2014 |access-date=October 3, 2021}}</ref> After a high-level B-Type game, various Nintendo characters perform in front of the cathedral.<ref name="meatfighter"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.oldschoolgamermagazine.com/mario-mania-game-cameos-for-the-fans-complete-collection-tetris-for-nes/ |title=Mario Mania: Game Cameos for the Fan's Complete Collection – Tetris for NES |last=Oxford |first=David |date=July 4, 2019 |work=Old School Gamer Magazine |access-date=October 3, 2021}}</ref> 

The definition of "beating the game" has changed over time with the development of novel controller methods designed for high-level play. After clearing around 1550 lines, the game is at risk of crashing due to inefficient multiplication operations.<ref name="meatfighter"/> Crashing the game in this way is popularly considered "beating the game", a feat first achieved on 21 December 2023 by 13-year-old [[Willis Gibson]], known by his online alias "Blue Scuti".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://kotaku.com/twitch-youtube-blue-scuti-tetris-kill-screen-nes-1851134043 |title=Three Decades Later, Someone Has Finally Beaten ''Tetris'' On NES |last=Winslow |first=Levi |date=January 2, 2024 |work=Kotaku |access-date=January 2, 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.popsci.com/technology/tetris-beat-kill-screen/ |title=A 13-year-old wunderkind is the first human to 'beat' Tetris |last=Paul |first=Andrew |date=January 2, 2024 |work=Popular Science |access-date=January 2, 2024}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-67871775 |title= Tetris: US teenager claims to be first to beat video game |agency= [[BBC News]] |date= 3 January 2024 |access-date= 3 January 2024 |last= Ferreira Santos |first= Sofia}}</ref> 

===Scoring===
The score received by each line clear is dependent on the level. Each type of clear, being a single, double, triple, or Tetris, has a base value which is multiplied by the number 1 higher than the current level. For any level <math>n</math>, a single will give <math>40(n+1) </math> points, a double will give <math>100(n+1)</math> points, a triple will give <math>300(n+1)</math> points, and a Tetris will give <math>1200(n+1)</math> points.<ref name="manual" /> The game also awards points for holding the down key to make pieces fall faster, awarding 1 point for every grid cell that a piece is continuously soft dropped.<ref name="manual" /> Unlike line clears, this does not scale by level.

This scoring convention makes scoring Tetrises much more efficient than scoring an equivalent amount of lines through smaller line clears. At level 0, a Tetris awards 300 points per line cleared, a triple awards 100 points per line cleared, a double awards 50 points per line cleared, and a single awards 40 points per line cleared. For example, a single in level 0 is worth 40 points and a Tetris worth 1,200 points. A single in level 9 is worth 400 points and a Tetris worth 12,000 points, and a single in level 29 is worth 1,200 points (same as a Tetris on level 0) and a Tetris on level 29 is worth 36,000 points.

==High-level play==
===Speed techniques===
[[File:Rolling grip.jpg|thumb|Inputs can be made rapidly by flicking the game controller from behind ("rolling") with as many successive fingers as needed to move the falling game piece to the desired location.]]
One of the most limiting factors in NES ''Tetris'' is the speed at which a tetromino can be moved left and right. On the NTSC version, when a movement key is pressed, the piece will instantly move one grid cell, stop for 16 frames due to delayed auto-shift, before moving again once every 6 frames, or 10 times per second.<ref>{{cite web |date=October 30, 2018 |title=What is DAS and Hyper Tapping in Tetris |url=https://simon.lc/what-is-das-and-hyper-tapping-in-tetris |access-date=2023-04-19 |website=Simon Laroche |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://meatfighter.com/nintendotetrisai/#The_Mechanics_of_Nintendo_Tetris |title=The Mechanics of Nintendo Tetris |access-date=June 14, 2024}}</ref> At higher levels, waiting for this delay is not feasible because the pieces fall too fast.

{{anchor|Hypertapping}}A technique known as "hypertapping" is used to circumvent this delay. When hypertapping, horizontal tetromino speed is maximized by rapidly tapping the [[D-pad]] more than 10 times per second.<ref name="kotaku">{{cite web |last=Gach |first=Ethan |date=October 22, 2018 |title=16-Year-Old Dethrones ''Tetris'' World Champion With Difficult Hyper-Tap Technique |url=https://kotaku.com/16-year-old-dethrones-tetris-world-champion-with-diffic-1829911215 |access-date=October 4, 2021 |work=[[Kotaku]]}}</ref> The technique involves flexing the [[bicep]] until it [[tremor]]s, so that the high-speed tremor taps the thumb on the D-pad.<ref name="sweet" /> [[Thor Aackerlund]] was the first hypertapper,<ref name="sweet" /> but the technique was very rare until it was popularized by Joseph Saelee in 2018.<ref name="karnadi">{{Cite web |last1=Karnadi |first1=Chris |title=Teens are rewriting what is possible in the world of competitive Tetris |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |date=2022-07-21 |url=https://www.polygon.com/23269073/competitive-classic-tetris-ctwc-jonas-neubauer-andy-michael-artiaga |language=en-US |access-date=2022-08-01 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Jacob Sweet of ''[[The New Yorker]]'' described hypertapping as "turning [the] thumb into a [[jackhammer]]."<ref name="sweet" />

In 2020, the "rolling" technique was developed by competitive NES ''Tetris'' player Chris "Cheez_fish" Martinez.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web |last=Bankhurst |first=Adam |date=April 29, 2021 |title=NES Tetris Players Are Using a Special Technique Called Rolling to Set New World Records |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/tetris-players-are-using-a-special-technique-called-rolling-to-set-new-world-records |access-date=July 19, 2022 |website=IGN |language=en}}</ref> When rolling, a stationary finger is placed on the D-pad, while the other hand's fingers are drummed across the back of the controller, pushing the buttons up into the stationary hand.<ref name="kotaku rolling">{{Cite web |last=Zwiezen |first=Zack |date=April 26, 2021 |title=NES Tetris Players Call It 'Rolling,' And They're Setting New World Records |url=https://kotaku.com/nes-tetris-players-call-it-rolling-and-theyre-setting-1846767518 |access-date=July 19, 2022 |website=[[Kotaku]] |language=en-us}}</ref> To reduce friction, a glove may be worn on the drumming hand.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Marshall |first=Jessica |date=November 16, 2023 |title=Boy Wonder: Stillwater teen places third in Classic Tetris World Championship |url=https://www.stwnewspress.com/news/boy-wonder-stillwater-teen-places-third-in-classic-tetris-world-championship/article_0a390482-83ef-11ee-9d4d-b777b200f759.html |access-date=December 31, 2023 |website=[[NewsPress|Stillwater News Press]] |language=en-us}}</ref> This technique is both much faster and less physically straining than hypertapping<ref name="kotaku rolling" />{{snd}}it allows pieces to be shifted horizontally up to 30 times per second, enabling play far past level 29. Since 2021, numerous world records have been achieved using the rolling technique, and rolling is used in tournaments such as the [[Classic Tetris World Championship]].<ref name=":1" />

