===History of major achievements===
In 2009, Harry Hong became the first independently verified person to achieve 999,999 points on an unmodified cartridge, known as a maxout score.<ref name="sweet" /> Earlier plausible but unverified max-out scores were claimed by [[Thor Aackerlund]] {{circa|1990}} and [[Jonas Neubauer]] {{circa|2002}}.<ref name="sweet"/>

[[File:NES Tetris falling speed by level.jpg|thumb|In the North American release, level&nbsp;29 is associated with an extreme increase in piece gravity.{{efn|name=PAL killscreen}}]]
The game pieces reach their maximum falling speed on level 29 on the NTSC version and 19 on the PAL version,<ref name=":0"/> when the speed suddenly doubles.<ref name="sweet"/> According to ''[[The New Yorker]]'', level 29 "seems intentionally impossible—a quick way for developers to end the game."<ref name="sweet"/> Because of this "soft wall", efficient play was required to accumulate points before level 29 ended the game.<ref name=":0"/> In the 2000s, level 29 came to be known as the game's "[[kill screen]]"<ref name="sweet"/>{{snd}}though this label was found to be a misnomer when the level was passed in the 2010s.<ref name="good"/>

==== Progression beyond level 29 ====
Aackerlund, a hypertapper, first demonstrated that level 29 could be beaten in 2011; he is shown reaching level 30 in the documentary film ''[[Ecstasy of Order: The Tetris Masters]]''.<ref name="sweet" /> From level 30, the game's level counter stops working correctly, further suggesting that the developers did not believe level 29 could be surpassed.<ref name=":0" /><ref name="good" /><ref name="sharma">{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BSloQyl8HBs |title=13-year-old Becomes First Human to Beat Tetris: All You Need to Know |date=January 4, 2024 |last=Sharma |first=Palki |publisher=[[Firstpost]] |via=[[YouTube]] |work=Vantage with Palki Sharma |accessdate=January 4, 2024}}</ref> Level 31 was first reached in 2018 by 15-year-old hypertapper Joseph Saelee who eventually cleared four more consecutive levels until level 35,<ref name="neumann">{{cite web |last=Neumann |first=Sean | website=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]] | date=October 19, 2018 | url=https://www.vice.com/en/article/5988gb/this-bartender-is-secretly-the-greatest-tetris-player-in-the-world | title=This Bartender Is Secretly the Greatest Tetris Player in the World |accessdate = January 4, 2024}}</ref> and by 2020 hypertappers had gone as far as level 38.<ref name="orland">{{cite web |last=Orland |first=Kyle |date=January 2, 2024 |title=34 years later, a 13-year-old hits the NES Tetris 'kill screen' |url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2024/01/someone-has-finally-beaten-nes-tetris/ |accessdate=January 4, 2024 |website=[[Ars Technica]]}}</ref> Kyle Orland of ''[[Ars Technica]]'' explains that because of the rolling technique introduced by Martinez in 2020, "players were getting good enough to effectively play indefinitely on the same 'Level 29' speed that had been considered an effective kill screen just a few years earlier."<ref name="orland" /> By 2022, the highest level reached was 95.<ref name="karnadi" />

The final matchup in the Classic Tetris World Championship in 2022 resulted in competitors Eric Tolt and [[Justin Yu]] both reaching two million points in a game and levels 73 and 69, respectively. To prevent extremely prolonged games, the CTWC has modified their competition cartridges in 2023 to include a "super killscreen" at level 39, where pieces reach the bottom of the well in only a sixth of a second - two blocks per frame.<ref>{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jiAb8sqrtDc |title=The Greatest Classic Tetris Game of All Time Just Happened |date=May 20, 2023 |language=en |time=1:57 |access-date=2024-01-16 |via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref><ref name="ctwc" />{{third-party inline|date=April 2024}}

