[[File:Tetris NES color glitch.jpg|thumb|right|The [[glitch]]ed [[Palette (computing)|palette]] of level 146{{efn|The level counter erroneously displays ''E9'' because level 146 is far [[Buffer over-read|outside the normal range]] of levels that were defined by the developers.<ref name="meatfighter"/><ref name="sharma" />{{rp|at=2m38s}}}} (the "dusk level") is so low contrast that the blocks appear "nigh-invisible".<ref>{{cite web |last=Randall |first=Harvey | website=[[PC Gamer]] | date=January 3, 2024 | url=https://www.pcgamer.com/after-34-years-a-13-year-old-prodigy-has-become-the-first-person-to-beat-tetris-by-reaching-the-holy-grail-of-high-level-play-a-true-killscreen/ | title=After 34 years, a 13 year-old prodigy has become the first person to 'beat' Tetris by reaching the holy grail of high-level play: a 'true killscreen' |accessdate = January 4, 2024}}</ref> It&nbsp;was not beaten for over a year after it was first reached.<ref name="orland"/>]]
In 2014, computer researcher Mike Birken published an analysis of ''Tetris''<nowiki/>'s game code, including details on [[Undocumented feature|unexpected behaviors]] that occur at very high levels.<ref name="meatfighter" /> 

An [[Integer overflow|integer overflow bug]] is first encountered at level 138, where [[Palette (computing)|color palettes]] would be loaded from unrelated areas of memory, creating unusual and unintended game piece colors. In particular, levels 146 and 148, nicknamed "dusk" and "charcoal" by players, feature black game pieces that are extremely [[Contrast (vision)|difficult to see]] against the black background, hindering further progression. Additionally, the score-counting code could [[Crash (computing)|crash]] the game after about 1550 lines are cleared, corresponding to level 155.<ref name="meatfighter" />

