===Competition===
{{see also|Classic Tetris World Championship}}
[[File:CTWC 2023.jpg|thumb|People playing ''Tetris'' competitively]]
The [[Nintendo World Championships|1990 Nintendo World Championships]] were based on A-Type ''Tetris'', ''[[Super Mario Bros.]]'', and ''[[Rad Racer]]''. In each round, contestants were given a total of six minutes to score as much as possible across all three games. As the ''Tetris'' score was multiplied 25 times in the final tally, the prevailing strategy was to rush through the other two games to spend all available time in ''Tetris''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.looper.com/296133/the-untold-truth-of-the-nintendo-world-championship/ |title=The Untold Truth Of The Nintendo World Championship |last=McGuire |first=Keegan |date=February 18, 2022 |website=[[Looper (website)|Looper]] |access-date=April 21, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |last=Nauert |first=Donn |date=June 1990 |title=The Biggest "Easter Egg" of All |url=https://archive.org/details/video-games-computer-entertainment-june-1990/page/38/mode/2up |magazine=[[VideoGames & Computer Entertainment]] |location= |publisher= |access-date=January 10, 2024}}</ref>

Since 2010, the NES version of ''Tetris'' has been featured in the annual [[Classic Tetris World Championship|Classic Tetris World Championship]] (CTWC), which consists of a one-on-one competition to score the most points. Specialized cartridges give both competitors the option to use the same piece sequence.<ref name="ctwc">{{cite web|url=http://thectwc.com/rules|title=Official Classic Tetris World Championship Site|access-date=October 22, 2023}}</ref>

Since 2017, the tournament Classic Tetris Monthly (CTM) has run monthly with the same one-on-one format as the CTWC. The CTM rules are more relaxed than those of the CTWC, allowing the usage of [[emulator]]s and third-party hardware.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Bennett-Cohen |first=Justin |date=2021-12-16 |title=The Classic Tetris Monthly Tournament: What Is It and How Do You Compete? |url=https://www.makeuseof.com/classic-tetris-monthly-tournament-explained/ |access-date=2023-04-18 |website=MUO |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":0" /> In both the CTWC and CTM, there is a cap at level 39, either by stopping play once level 39 is reached, or by a [[Video game modification|mod]] which implements a "Super Killscreen", doubling the drop speed at level 39.<ref>{{cite web |title=2023 CTWC – Official Rules |url=https://thectwc.com/rules/ |website=Classic Tetris World Championship |access-date=2024-05-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Rules |url=https://ctm.gg/rules/ |website=Classic Tetris Monthly |access-date=2024-05-02}}</ref>

