By 1989, about six companies claimed rights to create and distribute the ''Tetris'' software for home computers, game consoles, and handheld systems.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=From Russia with Litigation|magazine=[[Next Generation (magazine)|Next Generation]] |issue=26|date=February 1997|page=42}}</ref> [[Elektronorgtechnica|ELORG]], the Soviet bureau that held the ultimate copyright, claimed that none of the companies were legally entitled to produce an [[Arcade game|arcade]] version, and signed those rights over to [[Atari Games]]. Non-Japanese console and handheld rights were signed over to [[Nintendo]].

''Tetris'' was shown at the January 1988 [[Consumer Electronics Show]] in Las Vegas, where it was picked up by Dutch-born American games publisher [[Henk Rogers]], then based in Japan. This eventually led to an agreement brokered with Nintendo where ''Tetris'' became a [[launch game]] for [[Game Boy]] and bundled with every system.<ref name=guardian020609>{{cite web |last=Johnson |first=Bobbie | website=[[The Guardian]] | date=June 2, 2009 | url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/gamesblog/2009/jun/02/tetris-25anniversary-alexey-pajitnov | title=How Tetris conquered the world, block by block}}</ref>

===Implementation===
Pajitnov is credited for the "original concept, design and program"<ref name="manual"/> but was not directly involved in developing this version.<ref>{{cite web |last=Cohen |first=Rebecca | website=[[NBC News]] | date=January 5, 2024 | url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/tetris-creator-surprises-willis-gibson-teen-beat-game-rcna132387 | title=Teen who beat Tetris gets a surprise meeting with game's creator |access-date=January 7, 2024}}</ref>

The NES does not have hardware support for generating random numbers.<ref>{{cite conference |url=https://pcgworkshop.com/papers/2022/pcg2022_full_paper_4435__Entropy_Lost_Nintendos_Not_So_Random_Sequence_Of_32767_Bits.pdf |title=Entropy Lost: Nintendo's Not-So-Random Sequence of 32,767 Bits |last1=Ngo |first1=Trang |author-link1= |last2=Williams |first2=Aaron |author-link2= |date=September 2022 |publisher=FDG '22: Proceedings of the 17th International Conference on the Foundations of Digital Games |book-title= |at=Article 65, pp. 1-10 |location= |conference= |id=}}</ref> A [[Pseudorandomness|pseudo-random number generator]] was implemented with a 16-bit [[linear-feedback shift register]]. The algorithm produces a close, but slightly uneven distribution of the seven types of game pieces; for every 224 pieces, there is one fewer long bar piece than would be expected from an even distribution.<ref name="meatfighter"/>

The game's code includes an unfinished and inaccessible two-player versus mode, which sends rows of garbage blocks (with one opening) to the bottom of the opponent's board when lines are cleared. This feature may have been scrapped due to a rushed development schedule, or to promote sales of the [[Game Link Cable]] which enables a two-player mode in Nintendo's [[Tetris (Game Boy video game)|Game Boy ''Tetris'']].<ref name="meatfighter"/>

===Music===
The soundtrack was written by Nintendo composer [[Hirokazu Tanaka]], who also scored the Game Boy version.<ref name=guardian020609/> Focusing on [[Music of Russia#18th and 19th century: Russian classical music|Russian classical music]],<ref name="sheff"/> the soundtrack features arrangements of "The Dance of the Sugar Plum Fairy" from [[Pyotr Ilyich Tchaikovsky]]'s ballet ''[[The Nutcracker]]'' and the overture from [[Georges Bizet]]'s opera ''[[Carmen]]''. The former replaces the arrangement of "[[Korobeiniki]]",<ref name="meatfighter"/> present in the Game Boy version, which has become strongly associated with ''Tetris''.<ref name=guardian020609/>

