==Legacy==
''[[Tetris & Dr. Mario]]'' (1994) features an enhanced remake of ''Tetris''.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/Nintendo_Power_Issue001-Issue127/Nintendo%20Power%20Issue%20070%20March%201995/page/n111/mode/2up?q=%22Tetris++Dr.+Mario%22|title=Now Playing|magazine=[[Nintendo Power]]|pages=102–107|volume=70|date=March 1995|access-date=June 30, 2021}}</ref> ''[[Tetris Effect#Connected|Tetris Effect: Connected]]'' (2020) includes a game mode that simulates the rules and visuals of ''Tetris'' for the NES.<ref name="viray">{{cite web |url=https://blog.playstation.com/2021/06/16/tetris-effect-connected-cross-platform-multiplayer-comes-to-ps4-this-july/ |title=Tetris Effect: Connected cross-platform multiplayer comes to PS4 this July |last=Viray |first=Aileen |date=June 16, 2021 |publisher=[[PlayStation#PlayStation Blog|PlayStation Blog]] |access-date=May 1, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=McWhertor|first=Michael|url=https://www.polygon.com/2020/10/28/21538025/tetris-effect-connected-classic-competitive-score-attack-nes|title=Tetris Effect: Connected pays homage to classic NES version|date=October 28, 2020|access-date=November 10, 2020|website=Polygon}}</ref>

The events that lead to Nintendo acquiring the license to publish a ''Tetris'' game for consoles are explained in BBC's TV documentary ''[[Tetris: From Russia with Love]]'' (2004), as well as a dramatic retelling in ''[[Tetris (film)|Tetris]]'' (2023).<ref>{{Cite web |last=Pingitore |first=Silvia |date=2023-03-19 |title=Interview with Tetris creator Alexey Pajitnov |url=https://the-shortlisted.co.uk/alexey-pajitnov-tetris-interview/ |access-date=2023-07-04 |language=en-GB}}</ref>

Since 2018, Nintendo's ''Tetris'' has experienced a resurgence in popularity with a younger audience. In 2020, more people attained a [[#Competition|max-out score]] than from 1990 to 2019 combined.<ref name="sweet"/>

===Use in research===
In 2018, 11 classic ''Tetris'' experts were instructed to play with the next piece preview window disabled ("no next box"). Their average score was found to drop dramatically, from 465,371 in control games to 6,457 with no next box. The author notes that even though one participant went on to become that year's world champion, no player was recorded scoring a Tetris{{efn|Scoring a ''tetris'' refers to the act of clearing four lines at once with a long bar piece.}} during any of the no next box games.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Berry |first1=Jacquelyn|date=June 2023 |title=No Next Box, No Experts: A Special Case of Epistemic Behavior in Extreme Tetris Expertise |url=https://www.journalofexpertise.org/articles/volume6_issue2/JoE_6_2_Berry.pdf |journal=Journal of Expertise |volume=6 |issue=2 |pages=164–175}}</ref>

In a 2023 study, 160 people were recorded playing classic ''Tetris''. The recordings suggested that novice players [[Blinking|blink]] less than usual while playing ''Tetris'', whereas experienced players remained closer to their normal blinking rate. The study concludes that a person's ''Tetris'' ability can be assessed by their blink rate during the first minute of play.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Guglielmo |first1=Gianluca |last2=Klincewicz |first2=Michal |last3=Huis in 't Veld |first3=Elisabeth |last4=Spronck |first4=Pieter |date=October 13, 2023 |title=Tracking Early Differences in Tetris Performance using Eye Aspect Ratio Extracted Blinks |url=https://philarchive.org/archive/GUGTED#.pdf |journal=[[IEEE Transactions on Games]] |volume= |issue= |pages= 1–8|doi=10.1109/TG.2023.3324511 |s2cid=264117001 |issn=2475-1502 }}</ref> In contrast, seven-time world champion [[Jonas Neubauer]] manually suppressed his [[corneal reflex|blink reflex]] while playing, leading to health concerns and his regular use of [[eye drop]]s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailybreeze.com/2017/11/25/seven-time-south-bay-tetris-world-champion-builds-internet-stardom-brick-by-brick-2/ |title=Seven-time South Bay Tetris world champion builds Internet stardom brick by brick |work=[[Daily Breeze]] |date=November 25, 2017 |access-date=May 30, 2024 |last=Green |first=Nick}}</ref>

